    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is indeed a bit temperamental, but most of the time the culprit is the heat level or the speed at which you add the butter. If the sauce feels like it’s collapsing right when you think it’s stable, it’s likely that the butter is melting too quickly or the pan is getting too hot. Try lowering the heat to a gentle simmer and whisking continuously while you add the butter in a thin, steady stream. Another common issue is the quality of the butter—make sure it’s a good quality, high-fat butter that emulsifies well. Also, check that your egg yolks are at room temperature before you start; cold yolks can cause the sauce to seize. If you keep the heat low and the whisking constant, the sauce should hold together much better.",
      "source": "target",
